---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-brazil', text: 'Leaving Brazilian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'currency-matters', text: 'Currency Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Brazil Digital Nomad Visa', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-brazil-digital-nomad-visa' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'portugueseSupport', header: 'Portuguese' },
  { key: 'usCoverage', header: 'US Coverage' },
  { key: 'brazilCoverage', header: 'Brazil Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', usCoverage: 'Strong', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', portugueseSupport: 'Limited', usCoverage: 'Excellent', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', portugueseSupport: 'Yes', usCoverage: 'Good', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$190/mo' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', portugueseSupport: 'Limited', usCoverage: 'Excellent', brazilCoverage: 'Limited', price: '$250/mo' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', portugueseSupport: 'Limited', usCoverage: 'Good', brazilCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$150/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Brazilian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Brazilian expats. From the US to Portugal, find coverage that works with Brazilian healthcare needs and currency considerations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Brazilian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Brazilians abroad face unique challenges: currency volatility, expensive destinations like the US, and varying healthcare standards. Here's how to stay protected."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/brazilian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Brazilian expats are concentrated in a few key destinations: the US, Portugal, Japan, UK, and other European countries. Your insurance needs vary dramatically by destination. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Brazilian expats. Strong US networks, Portuguese-language support, reliable global coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent US and UK coverage. Ideal for Brazilians in high-cost destinations.</li>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> Specifically designed for expats going to the US. Backed by Blue Cross Blue Shield with outstanding American networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good European coverage with Portuguese support. Solid choice for Brazilians in Portugal or other EU countries.</li>
    <li><strong>IMG Global:</strong> Budget-friendly alternative with adequate global coverage. Good for younger expats or those watching costs.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Going to the US?"
    description="US healthcare is dramatically more expensive than Brazil. A single hospitalization can cost $100,000+. Prioritize insurers with strong US networks and direct billing to avoid financial disaster."
    buttonText="Get US-Focused Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-brazil">Leaving Brazilian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Brazil's healthcare system has two components: public SUS and private planos de saúde. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>SUS (Sistema Único de Saúde)</h3>
  <p>
    SUS is available to everyone in Brazil, including non-residents who happen to be there. When you leave Brazil, you lose day-to-day access but can technically still use SUS during visits—there's no formal "deregistration." However, relying on SUS while living abroad isn't practical.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Health Plans (Planos de Saúde)</h3>
  <p>
    Brazilian private health insurance (Bradesco Saúde, SulAmérica, Amil, Unimed) is designed for Brazilian residents. International coverage is typically limited to 30-90 days of emergency treatment. Options when emigrating:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cancel:</strong> Most Brazilians cancel their plano when emigrating. You can rejoin when you return (subject to new underwriting)</li>
    <li><strong>Maintain for visits:</strong> Some keep a basic plan for Brazil trips, supplemented by international insurance</li>
    <li><strong>International plans from Brazilian insurers:</strong> Limited options exist (Porto Seguro has some international products)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>CPF and Tax Residency</h3>
  <p>
    Your CPF remains active regardless of residence. However, formally communicating your tax emigration to Receita Federal affects your obligations. Consult with a contador familiar with international taxation before leaving.
  </p>

  <h2 id="currency-matters">Currency Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Currency is a major consideration for Brazilian expats. The real has historically been volatile against the USD, EUR, and GBP. This affects insurance in several ways:
  </p>

  <h3>BRL vs USD Premiums</h3>
  <p>
    Most international insurers quote in USD or EUR. While premiums seem higher in real terms, you get stable coverage that doesn't erode with currency movements. A $1 million policy remains $1 million regardless of what the real does.
  </p>

  <h3>Paying from Brazil</h3>
  <p>
    If you're paying premiums from Brazilian income or savings, currency fluctuations directly impact affordability. Options:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Pay from foreign income (if you're earning abroad)</li>
    <li>Use an international credit card</li>
    <li>Consider the timing of premium payments relative to exchange rates</li>
    <li>Budget extra margin for currency volatility</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Price Reality Check</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      International insurance costs $150-300/month—expensive by Brazilian standards but often similar to or less than good planos de saúde. In the US, this coverage can save you from financial ruin if you need hospitalization.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Brazilian expats. They offer Portuguese-language support, strong US networks (critical for the large Brazilian community in Florida and the Northeast), and comprehensive global coverage. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    Direct billing works at major hospitals worldwide, and claims processing is efficient. Brazil coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats who want reliable global coverage with Portuguese support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent US and UK networks. The Bupa brand is well-recognized, and service quality is high. Plans are comprehensive, including mental health and maternity coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is higher than competitors, reflecting premium positioning. Portuguese support is limited, but English service is excellent.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats in the US or UK who want top-tier coverage and can afford premium pricing.
  </p>

  <h3>GeoBlue</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue is specifically designed for expats going to the US. Backed by Blue Cross Blue Shield, they have outstanding American networks—important since that's where many Brazilian expats end up. Coverage is designed around US healthcare realities.
  </p>

  <p>
    Less suitable for Brazilians going elsewhere, but excellent for the US-bound.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats specifically moving to the US who want optimal American healthcare access.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers strong European coverage at competitive prices—ideal for the large Brazilian community in Portugal. Portuguese-language support is available, and EU networks are comprehensive. Plans include mental health, maternity, and chronic condition management.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Brazilian expats in Portugal or other EU countries who want solid coverage at reasonable prices.
  </p>

  <h3>IMG Global</h3>
  <p>
    IMG Global offers budget-friendly international coverage. While networks and service may not match Cigna or Bupa, pricing is significantly lower. Good option for younger Brazilian expats or those prioritizing cost.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Cost-conscious Brazilian expats who need adequate coverage at lower premiums.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Pricing varies significantly based on age, destination, and coverage level. Get quotes from multiple providers to find the best value."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Brazilian expats should consider in key locations:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    The largest destination for Brazilian expats. US healthcare is extremely expensive—prioritize insurers with strong US networks and direct billing. Cigna, Bupa, and GeoBlue are top choices. Florida and Massachusetts have large Brazilian communities with Portuguese-speaking doctors.
  </p>

  <h3>Portugal</h3>
  <p>
    Growing rapidly due to cultural and language ties. Portugal's SNS (public health) is available to legal residents, but waiting times can be long. Many Brazilian expats supplement with private insurance. Allianz Care and Cigna both work well here.
  </p>

  <h3>Japan</h3>
  <p>
    Significant Brazilian community (dekasegi). Japanese health insurance is mandatory for residents, but international insurance can provide English/Portuguese-speaking support and evacuation options. Japan's healthcare is excellent but navigating it without Japanese is challenging.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to residents, but waiting times can be long. Many Brazilians supplement with private insurance for faster access to specialists. Bupa and Cigna have strong UK networks.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my plano de saúde abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Brazilian health plans only cover 30-90 days of emergency treatment abroad. For long-term stays, you need dedicated international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is SUS available when I visit Brazil?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Technically yes—SUS is universal. But relying on it while living abroad isn't practical. International insurance with Brazil coverage is better for visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I get USD or BRL coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">USD is better for most Brazilian expats. Currency depreciation has historically eroded BRL coverage value. Your premiums may fluctuate in real terms but coverage remains stable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Which insurer is best for the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">GeoBlue has the strongest US networks (Blue Cross Blue Shield). Cigna and Bupa are also excellent. All three offer direct billing at major US hospitals.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Portuguese-speaking doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In areas with large Brazilian communities (Florida, Lisbon, London), yes. International insurance covers any licensed doctor—look for Brazilian community health directories.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my INSS pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Brazil has social security agreements with several countries. Your contributions may count toward foreign pensions and vice versa. Contact INSS for your specific situation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Brazilian expats should prioritize USD-denominated coverage from reputable international insurers. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive coverage with Portuguese support. <strong>GeoBlue</strong> is ideal specifically for the US, while <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford it.
  </p>

  <p>
    For Portugal and Europe, <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value with Portuguese support. <strong>IMG Global</strong> is a solid budget option for younger expats.
  </p>

  <p>
    Whatever you choose, don't underestimate US healthcare costs if that's your destination. A single hospital stay without insurance can be financially devastating. The monthly premium is worth the protection.
  </p>

</PageShell>
